<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magecompendium.com/Spells/Rod_of_Mystical_Transvergance.htm">Summon Rod of Mystical Transvergence</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> is a <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>56</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->th level <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Luclin</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> dropped spell summons a <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magecompendium.com/Images/Rod_of_Mystical_Transvergance.jpg">Rod of Mystical Transvergence</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->, which has three right-click charges of <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magecompendium.com/Items/Effects/Mystical_Transvergance.htm">Mystical Transvergence</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->.  Each of the three charges gains the user 220 mana, but does 300 points of damage to them.  This damage <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>can</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> be reduced by <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Runes</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and some bard songs.<br>
<br>
Since each summoning costs 400 mana <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  (the link in MageCompendium is out of date)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, each rod yield 3 charges x 220 = 660 gross mana - 400 mana cost = 260 net mana gain for 900 damage.<br>
<br>
To the best of my knowledge, based on <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm28.showMessage?topicID=23.topic">Graffë's Wizard Library: Spell Casting Mastery</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  50% Specialization Conjuration</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> reduces the cost by 2.5%, so rods cost 390 and yield 270 net mana.<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  200% Specialization Conjuration</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> reduces the cost by 10%, so rods cost 360 and yield 300 net mana.<br>
<br>
With <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Spell Casting Mastery</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> these numbers become:<br>
<br>
SCM1 + 50% Spec: 5% savings, 380 cost, 280 net mana.<br>
SCM2 + 50% Spec: 10% savings, 360 cost, 300 net mana.<br>
SCM3 + 50% Spec: 17.5% savings, 330 cost, 330 net mana.<br>
<br>
SCM1 + 200% Spec: 12.5% savings, 350 cost, 310 net mana.<br>
SCM2 + 200% Spec: 17.5% savings, 330 cost, 330 net mana.<br>
SCM3 + 200% Spec: 25% savings, 300 cost, 360 net mana.<br>
<br>
Focus items with <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Mana Preservation III</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, such as the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Obolus Death Shroud</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, add another 40 mana cost savings and thus net mana.  The summoned focus earring does not save mana on summons.<br>
<br>
I have switched my specialization from <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Evocation</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Conjuration</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and recommend that strongly for all <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  ArchMagi</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  For the sake of simplifying the subsequent discussion, I am going to assume 200% conjuration specialization.<br>
<br>
300 mana / 900 damage ~= .33 mana per hit point regenerated for the Mage with 200% spec. conj.<br>
360 mana / 900 damage ~= .40 mana per hit point regenerated for the Mage with 200% and SMC3.<br>
660 mana / 900 damage ~= .73 mana per hit point regenerated for non-Mage.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> EDIT:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Summon Rod of Mystical Transvergence</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is 56th level.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ubalanzsonofanz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Balanz son of Anz</A> at: 6/11/02 4:30:28 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ubalanzsonofanz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Balanz son of Anz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Abuser of EZCodes</span><br>  Posts: 1415<br> <font color=#333333>(6/11/02 12:31:52 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerthelibrary.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=18.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Transvergence and The Single Mage</span><hr size=1> So you are soloing only with self buffs, and whenever you get near full health, you click a charge of Transvergence.  Standing naked HP regeneration seems to be 4 HP per tick, sitting appears to be 6, so call it 5 overall.  Either <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Phantasmal Armor</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> or <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Transon's Phantasmal Protection</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, adds another 5 hp/tick, so 10 hp/tick total, or a little over 3 extra mana per tick, better than <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Mental Clarity 3</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Add three levels of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Natural Regeneration</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> another mana per tick, the equivalent of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Mental Clarity 1</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> or <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Flowing Thought I</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
Here are some common buffs you might be able to trade for along the way to your campsite that last a while and add to your regeneration:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Skin Like Nature</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, 72 minutes, adds 2 HP/Tick = .67 mana/tick<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Natureskin</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, 81 minutes, add 4 HP/Tick = 1.33 mana/tick<br>
<br>
Note that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Protection of the Glades</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> overwrites <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Transon's Phantasmal Protection</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and has no HP regeneration component.  Thus, if you are not carrying any gems for the earlier <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Phantasmal Armor</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> spells, you directly gain only 3 mana/tick <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  (6 for PotG - 3 for PA)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and losing 5 HP/tick = 1.67 mana/tick, so a net gain of only 1.3 mana per tick for surrendering <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  TPP</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in favor of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  PotG</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
Also, note that rodding down and bandaging does not work, it is demonstrably better just to sit down and meditate instead, see: <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://pub6.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm30.showMessage?topicID=136.topic">2nd Basic Skill: Regeneration or First Aid?</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
Some rare items that have regeneration include:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Robe of the Enslaved Soul:</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, 5 HP/tick<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Zlandicar's Heart:</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> 5 HP/tick<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Tenth Coldain Ring:</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> 10 HP/tick<br>
And several items with the effect <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Aura of Battle</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, 2 HP/tick.<br>
<br>
These are not easy to obtain.<br>
 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ubalanzsonofanz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Balanz son of Anz</A> at: 6/11/02 4:56:06 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ubalanzsonofanz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Balanz son of Anz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Abuser of EZCodes</span><br>  Posts: 1416<br> <font color=#333333>(6/11/02 12:33:11 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerthelibrary.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=18.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Transvergence in Groups</span><hr size=1> In a group with a healer, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>      Rods of Transvergence</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> can be used to transfer mana to whichever caster needs it the most in a given moment, including the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>      Magician</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> themselves.  Low mana can be solved in a minute or so.  Every caster should have a rod, and, like the soloing mage, tap a charge when hitpoints approach full but mana does not.<br>
<br>
The <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>      Magician</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> should have the best hitpoint buffs available to them so they have more room to rod down when necessary, as should the healer and any other regular consumer of rods.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>      Dropping Rods:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
It is often not a good idea to open up a trade window with another player in order to hand them a rod.  First, it causes you to become the tradee's current target, which could be fatal in the middle of a fight.  Second, lag and packet loss can cause either of you to lock out temporarily, or even go link dead.  However, during down time in zones with low lag, trading with a sitting healer is often the fastest way to go, assuming you are safe for the moment.  At least you know a sitting character is not casting, and you are less likely to mess up their targetting.<br>
<br>
In general, though, one should drop rods on the ground for others to pick up without opening a trade window.  Luckily, rods has a distinct appearance on the ground, unlike most other summoned items.  There are two main techniques.<br>
<br>
If the area is not crowded, stare at a wall or up towards the ceiling, and click with the rod on your cursor towards the left third of your screen to drop a rod.  While the drop confirmation box does slow things down a bit, it is much better than accidentally dropping valuable equipment on the ground by accident.<br>
<br>
If the area is crowded with players or NPCS, or very laggy, you will find it difficult to drop an item as described above without accidentally opening up a trade window, which will screw everybody up.  An alternate technique is to fill every inventory slot in every bag with a single item, such as one summoned bandage.  Then, drop the rod onto your auto-equip area, and you will get the message, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>      &quot;Your inventory is full, there is no room for that item, so it fell to the ground.&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  This is very fast, and never fails.  Be careful when using consumable items, such as food, water, or malachite, to have a stack of them in an earlier inventory slot, so that consuming that item does not accidentally free up an inventory slot.<br>
<br>
Might be useful in this case to make a hot key something along these lines:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>      :drops a rod at his feet.<br>
/say Rods at feet!<br>
/gsay Rods at feet!<br>
/3 Rods at feet!</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Or some combination of the above <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>      (3 is my raid channel)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
Another useful hotkey I have found for demanding a heal is:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>      /gsay No HP, No mana, No Rods!<br>
/3 No HP, No Mana, No Rods!</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>      When to drop rods:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
This is primarily a matter of communication.  If for some reason you find yourself near full mana, might as well drop your current rod, and make another.  Likewise, use a charge whenever your hitpoints are close to full.  When I make a rod I usually take a hit off of it <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>      (consume a charge)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> first so my mana remains up.  Other casters will usually make their needs clear, either by calling their mana <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>      (LOM, OOM, Low on mana, 40% mana, etc.)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, or simply demanding a rod <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>      (Rod plz!)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  The healer <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>always</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> has priority for rods, because without healer mana, no one else gets rods.<br>
<br>
Never let your mana go much below 20%, so that you can drop your current rod and immediately summon another.  If you do not have enough mana left to summon a new rod, the house of cards collapse until you do.  Likewise, the healer need to retain enough mana to heal themselves at least once.<br>
<br>
During fights, it is generally a bad idea to let your health go much below 40%, as you may get low health aggro, especially if you sit to med.  If it is down time in a safe spot between pulls, and you have a cleric, you can rod down to only a few hitpoints and then get a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>      Complete Heal</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  This is very effective, and will be discussed in more detail later.<br>
<br>
As a rough rule of thumb, I try to consume one rod for each rod I export.  Assuming 200% conjuration specialization, that is 600 mana cost for 660 gross mana for you, 900 HP down, but still 60 net mana gain for you, and 660 mana for them.  Alternately, taking a hit off each rod before you drop it means they cost you only 300 - 220 = 80 net mana per rod for 300 HP.  Either way, rod production leaves your mana pool nearly constant.<br>
<br>
An important advantage of using rods combined with healing to regenerate mana is that it can be done standing up, and thus avoiding sitting aggro.<br>
 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ubalanzsonofanz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Balanz son of Anz</A> at: 6/11/02 5:04:15 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ubalanzsonofanz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Balanz son of Anz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Abuser of EZCodes</span><br>  Posts: 1417<br> <font color=#333333>(6/11/02 12:34:47 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerthelibrary.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=18.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Clerical Rodding</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> The Complete Heal/Rod Cycle:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Because of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Complete Heal</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, when there is safe down time, clerics are the most effective users of down time.  They also have the best HP buffs.  Barring raid level buffs, I often find myself with around 2100-2400 HP, or 7 charges of transvergence.  Without enchanter buffs, my mana pool appears to be around 3400 mana, or about 9 rods.  Lets suppose the buffed cleric has about 3400 HP, or 11 charges of transvergence, or 18 charges between the two of us.<br>
<br>
If we both rod down to under 300 HP each:<br>
<br>
18 charges = 6 rods x 360 mana per rod = 2160 my mana, plus two complete heals @ 360 mana each <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (200% spec. Abj.)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> = 2,880 total mana cost.<br>
18 charges x 220 mana per charge = 3,960 gross mana - 2,880 = 1,080 mana per CH/rod cycle.<br>
<br>
Assuming that we are both start at 20% mana and near full health, it would take about three such cycles to bring both of us back to full mana.  With better HP buffs it is even more efficient.  With 2900 HP for me I can eat 9 charges, and 3750 HP for the cleric, they can eat 12 charges, so 7 rods and two complete heals for 3,240 mana cost, gaining 4,620 gross mana or 1,380 net mana per CH/rod cycle.<br>
<br>
AA skills have a profound effect on this.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Spell Casting Mastery 3</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> would bring the first example to 3,960 gross - 2,400 cost = 1,560 net gain per CH/rod cycle, or with better HP buffs, 1,860 mana per CH/rod cycle.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Quick Summoning 2</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> would reduce the time for a each cycle.<br>
<br>
Assuming it takes about 6 seconds <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (one tick)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to summon, hand off, and consume a rod, with two complete heals at the end, in 6 x 6 = 36 seconds for rods + 20 seconds for two complete heals, or <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> over a thousand group mana per minute</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, or 100 mana / tick.<br>
<br>
So the next time your cleric calls <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;Low Mana,&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the proper response should be, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;That's no excuse!&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Other heals:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
During a fight, rodding down to about 40% health, I could eat 5 charges, the healer 7, for 4 rods and two complete heals, costing 2,160 mana, grossing 2,640 or only 480 net mana gain per cycle, not near so efficient, so other heals come to mind.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Superior Healing</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is a 34th level, 583 point targeted heal for 250 mana.  It counters the HP loss of two charges of a rod.  2/3 of a rod costs 240 mana, plus 225 mana for the heal, or 465 mana to get 440 mana.  Not a good deal except to transfer mana away from the mage and cleric to a third party who needs it <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (like an enchanter)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Word of Healing</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is a 49th level, 500 point group heal for 600 mana, and might be effective if there are lots of casters rodding.  I rarely see it used though, I suspect because of aggro.  If four casters each ate a rod, then the group gains 4 x 660 mana = 2,640 mana gross, minus 4 x 360 = 1,440 mana for the rods, plus 540 mana for the heal <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (Spec. Abj.)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, = 660 gain for the group, leaving 400 damage each to regenerate by other means.  Might be useful in a caster group on raids.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Remedy</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is 51st level, 438 point heal for 175 mana, and cancels out two charges of a rod nicely. 2/3 of a rod costs 240 mana, plus 160 mana <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (spec. abj.)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> = 400 mana cost to gain 440 mana, = 40 net gain, not terribly appealing, but again useful to transfer mana to a third party.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Divine Light</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is a 53rd level, 900 point heal for 350 mana.  Eating one rod, this would cost 360 for the rod, plus 315 for the heal, or 675 mana to gain 660.  Again, not efficient.<br>
<br>
So direct heals are not generally efficient, except to transfer mana to third parties.<br>
<br>
However, regeneration buffs are another story entirely:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Celestial Healing</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is 44th level spell that regenerates about 750 HP for 225 mana.  Assuming the target has just eaten a rod, that is 360 mana cost for the rod, 220 for the healing <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (50% Spec. Alt)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> or 560 cost for 660 gross, or 100 net main gained in 4 ticks for a net 150 HP loss.  100 mana in four ticks is comparable to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Flowing Thought 25</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and is usuable when time is of the essence.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Celestial Elixer</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is 59th level spell that regenerates about a 1,000 HP for 300 mana in 4 ticks.  This more than compensates for eating a rod.  One rod for 360 mana, plus one elixer for 270 mana, or 630 mana to gain 660 mana, or 30 mana in 4 ticks, or still better than <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Flowing Thought 7</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
As 150 damage takes 10 ticks to heal naturally, I conclude that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Celestial HEALING</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is better suited for the job at hand, although either one will work.<br>
